1
00:00:21,840 --> 00:00:24,440
( Humming Stops )

2
00:01:33,080 --> 00:01:35,160
Michael Scott Kelvin,
What are you doing?

3
00:01:38,080 --> 00:01:40,880
What the hell are you
trying to do, kill us?

4
00:01:40,880 --> 00:01:43,480
- Christ!
- Beth and I were just playing, Mom.

5
00:01:44,000 --> 00:01:46,080
Mikey, you promised you
wouldn't do this again.

6
00:01:46,080 --> 00:01:50,960
Beth wanted to see it.
Tell her it was your idea.

7
00:01:54,400 --> 00:01:57,760
You stop trying
to blame your sister

8
00:01:57,760 --> 00:02:00,120
Look at me.
You've ruined everything.

9
00:02:00,640 --> 00:02:02,200
You clean up
this mess, right now!

10
00:02:02,960 --> 00:02:05,840
We'll deal with your punishment
when your father gets home.

11
00:02:05,840 --> 00:02:07,400
Beth, come on.

12
00:02:10,000 --> 00:02:12,600
I hate you!
You don't care about me!

13
00:02:12,600 --> 00:02:14,160
You're not my real mother!

14
00:02:24,040 --> 00:02:26,640
Why didn't you tell her you did it?

15
00:02:26,640 --> 00:02:28,720
Give me back Alice, Mikey.

16
00:02:28,720 --> 00:02:31,320
She never punishes you.
Never, ever!

17
00:02:31,840 --> 00:02:33,400
Give it, Mikey. Give it.

18
00:02:33,400 --> 00:02:36,000
You're my sister.
You should have been on my side!

19
00:02:36,000 --> 00:02:38,080
You're not my real brother!

20
00:02:39,120 --> 00:02:42,760
Mommy! Mikey went outside
without permission.

21
00:02:43,280 --> 00:02:45,880
Mommy! Gimme back!
She's mine.

22
00:02:49,000 --> 00:02:50,040
Make me, Beth.

23
00:02:50,560 --> 00:02:53,160
- Mikey, give me back my doll.
- Forget it!

24
00:02:58,360 --> 00:02:59,920
Gimme back my doll, Mikey.

25
00:02:59,920 --> 00:03:02,000
Come on, baby.
Come and get it.

26
00:03:02,000 --> 00:03:03,560
Give it, Mikey.

27
00:03:03,560 --> 00:03:05,120
I bet you can't get it.

28
00:03:05,120 --> 00:03:07,720
Mikey, give me back my doll.

29
00:03:08,240 --> 00:03:09,080
Come and get it.

30
00:03:09,080 --> 00:03:10,840
I hope your doll likes to swim.

31
00:03:13,960 --> 00:03:15,520
She's drowning, Beth.

32
00:03:18,120 --> 00:03:20,720
Stop it! Stop it!

33
00:03:21,240 --> 00:03:22,800
Stop it!

34
00:03:27,480 --> 00:03:28,520
Ah!

35
00:03:32,680 --> 00:03:36,320
Mikey! Help me!

36
00:03:38,400 --> 00:03:39,960
Mommy!

37
00:03:40,480 --> 00:03:41,520
Mommy!

38
00:03:43,080 --> 00:03:44,640
Help me!

39
00:03:45,680 --> 00:03:47,240
( Choking )

40
00:03:49,840 --> 00:03:51,400
( Choking Stops )

41
00:03:56,600 --> 00:03:58,160
I shouldn't even be thinking this.

42
00:03:59,200 --> 00:04:01,800
But sometimes I think
adopting him was a mistake.

43
00:04:02,840 --> 00:04:04,920
I mean, I just don't know what--

44
00:04:05,440 --> 00:04:08,040
Jo? Joanna?

45
00:04:09,080 --> 00:04:10,960
These damn things.

46
00:04:15,320 --> 00:04:17,080
Michael, what have I
told you about knocking?

47
00:04:17,080 --> 00:04:19,480
You don't love me anymore.

48
00:04:19,480 --> 00:04:23,120
Of course, I do. Your father
and I love you so very much.

49
00:04:23,640 --> 00:04:25,200
Then why do you
always punish me?

50
00:04:25,720 --> 00:04:28,840
Look, we'll talk about this
when your father gets home.

51
00:04:33,520 --> 00:04:35,080
( Start Hair Dryer )

52
00:04:35,600 --> 00:04:37,160
That just means I'm in trouble.

53
00:04:37,680 --> 00:04:40,280
Mikey, Put that down.
That's not funny.

54
00:04:41,320 --> 00:04:42,640
Daddy's on his way home.

55
00:04:42,640 --> 00:04:46,000
- That's not a toy.
- I know that.

56
00:04:46,000 --> 00:04:47,040
Mikey, no!

57
00:05:22,920 --> 00:05:23,960
( Birds Chirping )

58
00:05:40,080 --> 00:05:42,680
It's time for a little hide and seek.

59
00:05:42,680 --> 00:05:44,240
( Audience Laughing )

60
00:05:44,760 --> 00:05:46,320
DAD: I'm home!

61
00:05:47,360 --> 00:05:49,440
Daddy's home!

62
00:05:49,440 --> 00:05:52,560
What have you been
doing all day?

63
00:05:52,560 --> 00:05:55,680
- Waiting for you.
- Where's your mom?

64
00:05:55,680 --> 00:05:57,760
She's upstairs taking a bath.

65
00:05:58,280 --> 00:05:59,840
Hey, you been playing baseball?

66
00:05:59,840 --> 00:06:00,880
No.

67
00:06:06,080 --> 00:06:07,640
Oh, my God!

68
00:06:10,240 --> 00:06:11,280
Ohh!

69
00:06:19,080 --> 00:06:21,680
- Mi-- Mikey.
- See ya, champ.

70
00:06:23,040 --> 00:06:24,280
No!

71
00:06:38,840 --> 00:06:40,920
I can't believe this happened.

72
00:06:40,920 --> 00:06:43,000
This is terrible!

73
00:06:43,000 --> 00:06:44,040
Poor Mikey!

74
00:06:45,600 --> 00:06:47,160
What's this world coming to?

75
00:06:47,680 --> 00:06:49,240
( Police Radio in Background )

76
00:06:53,400 --> 00:06:55,480
Collins, who's she?

77
00:06:56,000 --> 00:06:57,040
A neighbor.

78
00:06:57,560 --> 00:06:58,600
Hmm.

79
00:07:01,720 --> 00:07:02,760
Is it pretty bad?

80
00:07:04,320 --> 00:07:05,360
Yeah.

81
00:07:06,400 --> 00:07:07,440
Well, let's go.

82
00:07:09,000 --> 00:07:10,040
This way.

83
00:07:11,080 --> 00:07:14,200
It looks like he saw his little girl
in the pool and panicked.

84
00:07:14,200 --> 00:07:16,800
Yeah, but the window didn't
do that to his head.

85
00:07:17,840 --> 00:07:20,440
Something like a two-by-four did.

86
00:07:23,040 --> 00:07:24,600
Grace Kelvin...

87
00:07:25,120 --> 00:07:26,160
age 32.

88
00:07:26,680 --> 00:07:28,240
Been fried.

89
00:07:29,280 --> 00:07:30,320
This is it, Collins?

90
00:07:30,840 --> 00:07:31,880
No.

91
00:07:32,400 --> 00:07:33,960
There's one more.

92
00:07:43,840 --> 00:07:45,400
What's your name, son?

93
00:07:48,520 --> 00:07:50,600
You see, I'm a detective.

94
00:07:51,120 --> 00:07:52,680
It's my job to catch the guy.

95
00:07:53,200 --> 00:07:54,760
That did this to your family.

96
00:07:56,320 --> 00:07:58,400
Detective Reynolds.

97
00:07:58,920 --> 00:08:00,480
Miss Harlig...

98
00:08:00,480 --> 00:08:01,760
always a pleasure.

99
00:08:03,920 --> 00:08:05,480
You must be Mikey; right?

100
00:08:08,280 --> 00:08:09,840
Come here.

101
00:08:27,520 --> 00:08:28,560
Mikey, Mikey.

102
00:08:29,080 --> 00:08:31,160
Did you see anybody you
didn't know hanging around?

103
00:08:31,680 --> 00:08:34,000
Now's not the time
for this, Jake.

104
00:08:34,000 --> 00:08:36,360
Katherine, would you knock it off?

105
00:08:36,360 --> 00:08:41,560
He had bushy hair,
a mustache, and a red jacket.

106
00:08:42,080 --> 00:08:43,640
You did see him, then?

107
00:08:44,160 --> 00:08:46,240
I came home from the park.

108
00:08:46,760 --> 00:08:50,920
He was running out of my house,
and he drove away.

109
00:08:51,440 --> 00:08:53,000
What did the car look like?

110
00:08:53,520 --> 00:08:56,120
It was big and brown.

111
00:08:56,880 --> 00:08:59,240
Is that all?
You've been a big help.

112
00:09:04,440 --> 00:09:05,480
Reynolds, the corner's about done.

113
00:09:06,000 --> 00:09:08,600
They're dusting now.
The they'll seal I off.

114
00:09:08,600 --> 00:09:10,160
There was nothing stolen.

115
00:09:12,240 --> 00:09:15,360
We've got bodies
separated so far apart.

116
00:09:15,880 --> 00:09:17,440
What are you saying?

117
00:09:18,480 --> 00:09:21,080
It's like the victims
knew the killer.

118
00:09:23,680 --> 00:09:26,800
I want to go take a bath.
You watch Beth for me.

119
00:09:26,800 --> 00:09:28,360
Okay, Mommy.

120
00:09:29,400 --> 00:09:33,040
I'm home, everybody!
Daddy! Daddy!

121
00:09:33,560 --> 00:09:35,640
Hey, champ.
What you been up to?

122
00:09:36,680 --> 00:09:38,760
Waiting for you.

123
00:09:39,280 --> 00:09:40,840
Where's your mom?

124
00:09:40,840 --> 00:09:42,400
In the bathtub.

125
00:09:44,480 --> 00:09:45,000
Oh.

126
00:09:45,000 --> 00:09:47,080
I'm gonna put these here.

127
00:09:50,200 --> 00:09:51,760
Who's that, Mikey?

128
00:09:52,280 --> 00:09:55,400
I don't know. A stranger.

129
00:09:55,400 --> 00:09:57,480
Have you seen him before?

130
00:09:57,480 --> 00:10:00,080
No. Mommy doesn't
know who he is.

131
00:10:01,120 --> 00:10:03,200
I have to go outside.

132
00:10:03,720 --> 00:10:05,800
Why do you
have to go outside?

133
00:10:07,880 --> 00:10:11,000
I'm not supposed
to see what happens.

134
00:10:12,040 --> 00:10:13,600
And what's that?

135
00:10:14,120 --> 00:10:17,240
He's gonna do something
to my family...

136
00:10:17,760 --> 00:10:19,840
kill them.

137
00:10:24,000 --> 00:10:26,600
How do you feel
about that man?

138
00:10:29,720 --> 00:10:31,280
I hate him.

139
00:10:32,840 --> 00:10:33,880
I hate him!

140
00:10:34,920 --> 00:10:38,360
I hate him! I hate him!
I hate him!

141
00:10:39,080 --> 00:10:42,200
I've just had my final session
with Michael Kelvin.

142
00:10:42,200 --> 00:10:43,760
The boy's going through
a great trauma,

143
00:10:43,760 --> 00:10:46,640
and there's still quite
a bit of emotional scarring.

144
00:10:47,400 --> 00:10:49,480
Are you sure?
He's ready to leave?

145
00:10:49,480 --> 00:10:50,520
I believe so.

146
00:10:51,560 --> 00:10:55,200
I'd suggest you get him
placed with adoptive parents

147
00:10:55,720 --> 00:10:57,800
as quickly as you can.

148
00:10:57,800 --> 00:11:01,960
Mikey just needs a good,
stable home.

149
00:11:01,960 --> 00:11:03,520
I'm not a blood relative.

150
00:11:03,520 --> 00:11:05,600
Your his mother's sister!

151
00:11:06,640 --> 00:11:09,240
That kid was adopted.

152
00:11:10,080 --> 00:11:11,840
Are you positive?

153
00:11:12,880 --> 00:11:16,520
Michael hasn't said anything to
any of us about being adopted.

154
00:11:17,040 --> 00:11:19,120
They took him away
from his real parents!

155
00:11:19,120 --> 00:11:23,280
He was abused or something.
Gracie never knew for sure.

156
00:11:25,880 --> 00:11:29,000
Kelsey, I know
that the last few days

157
00:11:29,000 --> 00:11:31,080
have been very difficult for you.

158
00:11:32,120 --> 00:11:34,200
But you're all he has.

159
00:11:34,720 --> 00:11:36,800
You know that your sister
would have wanted you to--

160
00:11:36,800 --> 00:11:39,400
I'm not taking him. Not a chance.

161
00:11:39,400 --> 00:11:40,960
Why not?

162
00:11:43,560 --> 00:11:47,720
Look. You can't make me
that that kid, can you?

163
00:11:49,800 --> 00:11:51,360
No, I can't.

164
00:11:51,880 --> 00:11:56,560
Good. The kiss him
good-bye for me.

165
00:12:05,400 --> 00:12:08,000
God, I hate airports.
I hate coming here.

166
00:12:08,000 --> 00:12:10,600
No matter what time you leave,
you're always late.

167
00:12:10,600 --> 00:12:13,200
Jesus, there's something wrong
with this damn flash!

168
00:12:13,200 --> 00:12:17,360
We're not gonna need
the damn flash if we miss him.

169
00:12:18,920 --> 00:12:20,480
Son of a bitch.

170
00:12:21,000 --> 00:12:23,080
Oh, son of a bitch. There it is!

171
00:12:23,080 --> 00:12:25,680
You're gonna have to start
watching your language.

172
00:12:25,680 --> 00:12:27,240
Yes, mother.

173
00:12:30,360 --> 00:12:31,920
WOMAN: There he is.

174
00:12:36,600 --> 00:12:38,680
Mikey, this is the Trentons.

175
00:12:42,520 --> 00:12:45,960
Are you my
new mommy and daddy?

176
00:12:52,720 --> 00:12:55,320
- Go on.
- Oh, Mikey. Here's a present.

177
00:12:55,840 --> 00:12:59,480
Thanks, Mr. Trenton. It's great!

178
00:13:00,000 --> 00:13:02,080
You don't have to
call me "Mr. Trenton."

179
00:13:02,600 --> 00:13:04,680
What do you want me
to call me?

180
00:13:05,200 --> 00:13:09,680
- Um...
- You can start with Neil and Rachel.

181
00:13:09,680 --> 00:13:11,680
Okay, Rachel.

182
00:13:13,520 --> 00:13:14,560
There's my stuff.

183
00:13:15,080 --> 00:13:17,680
I was right. He's a ballplayer.

184
00:13:19,760 --> 00:13:21,320
So, do you like to pitch?

185
00:13:21,320 --> 00:13:24,440
Yeah. But I'm a better hitter.

186
00:13:30,160 --> 00:13:33,280
We don't have a pool,
but there is a lake.

187
00:13:33,280 --> 00:13:36,400
Cool. Swimming's one
of my favorite things.

188
00:13:43,160 --> 00:13:45,240
This is it, Mikey. We're home.

189
00:13:46,440 --> 00:13:47,440
Wow!

190
00:13:49,400 --> 00:13:51,480
It's really neat.

191
00:13:52,000 --> 00:13:54,600
Welcome to your new home, chief.

192
00:13:54,600 --> 00:13:57,200
I think you're gonna be
real happy here.

193
00:14:00,320 --> 00:14:03,440
Here we are.

194
00:14:03,960 --> 00:14:04,480
Hi!

195
00:14:05,000 --> 00:14:06,040
Welcome!

196
00:14:06,560 --> 00:14:10,200
Mikey, this is Mrs. Owens.
She lives next door.

197
00:14:10,200 --> 00:14:12,040
- Hi.
- Hi.

198
00:14:12,040 --> 00:14:13,320
And this is Ben.

199
00:14:13,840 --> 00:14:15,920
Ben will be in
your class at school.

200
00:14:15,920 --> 00:14:17,200
- Hi.
- Hi.

201
00:14:18,000 --> 00:14:19,560
Alright!

202
00:14:19,560 --> 00:14:22,680
I just know the two of you
are gonna be best of friends.

203
00:14:22,680 --> 00:14:26,320
Mrs. Owens also has a
daughter named Jessie.

204
00:14:26,320 --> 00:14:27,880
You want to see your room?

205
00:14:27,880 --> 00:14:31,000
- Ben on come, too.
- Okay.

206
00:14:32,040 --> 00:14:33,080
Where's your sister?

207
00:14:33,080 --> 00:14:34,120
She had to go away to school.

208
00:14:34,640 --> 00:14:35,680
Oh.

209
00:14:36,960 --> 00:14:39,840
Wow, this is neat!

210
00:14:39,840 --> 00:14:41,920
This is Rachel's job.

211
00:14:41,920 --> 00:14:44,000
She creates these
aquariums for people.

212
00:14:44,000 --> 00:14:46,600
She takes care of 'em.

213
00:14:46,600 --> 00:14:48,680
Maybe you can he me, Mikey.

214
00:14:49,720 --> 00:14:51,280
What's that?

215
00:14:51,280 --> 00:14:53,360
That's a mommy fish
and her new babies.

216
00:14:53,360 --> 00:14:55,440
Why are they separated?

217
00:14:55,440 --> 00:14:58,040
Because this kind of
fish eats its babies.

218
00:14:58,040 --> 00:15:00,120
- Really?
- Gross.

219
00:15:00,640 --> 00:15:02,720
Can I take care of the baby fish?

220
00:15:02,720 --> 00:15:03,760
Sure.

221
00:15:03,760 --> 00:15:05,320
( Doorbell Ringing )

222
00:15:07,400 --> 00:15:09,480
- Hi, Rachel.
- Shawn, thanks.

223
00:15:11,040 --> 00:15:12,080
No problem.

224
00:15:12,600 --> 00:15:14,680
Mikey, I want you to meet
my best friend, Shawn.

225
00:15:14,680 --> 00:15:15,430
Hi.

226
00:15:16,240 --> 00:15:18,840
Miss Gilder's a teacher.
She teaches fourth grade.

227
00:15:18,840 --> 00:15:20,400
Is she gonna be my teacher?

228
00:15:20,920 --> 00:15:24,040
Yes. But don't expect any favors

229
00:15:24,040 --> 00:15:26,120
because I'm friends with your mom.

230
00:15:26,120 --> 00:15:27,160
I love school.

231
00:15:27,160 --> 00:15:28,200
That's good.

232
00:15:28,720 --> 00:15:31,320
Mikey, you want to see
your room or what?

233
00:15:36,520 --> 00:15:39,640
Well, how are you doing, Mom?

234
00:15:40,160 --> 00:15:41,720
He seems like a good kid.

235
00:15:41,720 --> 00:15:43,280
- You think so?
- Uh-huh.

236
00:15:43,800 --> 00:15:46,400
You know more about kids
than I do, that's for sure.

237
00:15:46,920 --> 00:15:51,600
This has all happened so fast.

238
00:15:51,600 --> 00:15:54,200
I haven't even had times
to childproof the house yet.

239
00:15:54,720 --> 00:15:56,800
You are going to make
a great mother.

240
00:15:57,320 --> 00:15:58,880
A great mother!

241
00:15:58,880 --> 00:16:00,960
Then why am I do nervous?

242
00:16:02,000 --> 00:16:04,280
I think it's kind of
natural; don't you?

243
00:16:04,280 --> 00:16:06,680
You and Neil have wanted
a family for five years.

244
00:16:06,680 --> 00:16:08,760
A baby, yes.

245
00:16:09,280 --> 00:16:12,400
But this child's been
shuffled around so much.

246
00:16:12,920 --> 00:16:13,960
Yeah.

247
00:16:15,520 --> 00:16:17,600
He'll do okay.

248
00:16:17,600 --> 00:16:18,640
Just love him.

249
00:16:21,240 --> 00:16:23,840
- You're right.
- Uh-huh.

250
00:16:23,840 --> 00:16:25,920
He's no different than any other kid.

251
00:16:30,080 --> 00:16:31,640
Did you brush your teeth?

252
00:16:32,160 --> 00:16:33,200
Uh-huh.

253
00:16:33,200 --> 00:16:35,280
Good. Then it's time
to hit the hay.

254
00:16:36,320 --> 00:16:37,880
Good night, Mikey.

255
00:16:38,400 --> 00:16:39,960
Mom, Dad.

256
00:16:44,120 --> 00:16:45,160
Thanks.

257
00:16:48,280 --> 00:16:50,600
You're welcome.

258
00:16:51,400 --> 00:16:52,960
Lights out, buddy.

259
00:17:06,200 --> 00:17:08,040
Can you believe what
a great kid he is?

260
00:17:12,200 --> 00:17:13,760
I think we really lucked out.

261
00:17:14,280 --> 00:17:15,320
Yeah.

262
00:17:20,520 --> 00:17:23,120
So have you kept up
on all your reading?

263
00:17:23,120 --> 00:17:24,680
Uh-huh.

264
00:17:25,720 --> 00:17:27,000
What do you think about that

265
00:17:27,000 --> 00:17:29,880
fourth stage of development
in the laughler book?

266
00:17:30,400 --> 00:17:31,960
Fascinating.

267
00:17:39,760 --> 00:17:42,360
Rachel, there is no
fourth stage of development

268
00:17:42,880 --> 00:17:44,440
in the laughler book.

269
00:17:44,440 --> 00:17:46,520
I don't need to read any book

270
00:17:47,040 --> 00:17:48,600
to tell me how to be a good mother.

271
00:17:48,600 --> 00:17:50,160
A little help couldn't hurt.

272
00:17:50,160 --> 00:17:51,720
You read too much, Trenton.

273
00:17:52,240 --> 00:17:53,800
Somebody's got to do it.

274
00:17:59,520 --> 00:18:01,600
It's been a long time, Neil.

275
00:18:02,640 --> 00:18:04,720
It'll be better now.

276
00:18:24,480 --> 00:18:26,560
( Rachel Laughing in Background )

277
00:18:39,560 --> 00:18:41,360
( Background Conversations )

278
00:18:44,240 --> 00:18:46,320
Now we're gonna shoot
some bad guys.

279
00:18:46,320 --> 00:18:48,400
Did you do this with your dad?

280
00:18:48,400 --> 00:18:50,480
We didn't have the indian guides,

281
00:18:50,480 --> 00:18:53,080
but I used to go out
riding with him a lot.

282
00:18:53,600 --> 00:18:54,640
We did a lot of
fun things together,

283
00:18:54,640 --> 00:18:56,720
just like you and I are going to.

284
00:18:58,800 --> 00:19:00,880
But what about the other kid?

285
00:19:01,400 --> 00:19:02,960
What other kid?

286
00:19:02,960 --> 00:19:05,040
The kid you had before me.

287
00:19:05,040 --> 00:19:09,200
Mikey, listen to me.
There was no other kid.

288
00:19:09,200 --> 00:19:11,280
But what about
all the stuff in my room?

289
00:19:11,280 --> 00:19:13,360
We brought all that stuff for you.

290
00:19:14,920 --> 00:19:18,560
Rachel and I have wanted
a child for a very long time.

291
00:19:18,560 --> 00:19:20,640
Why didn't you just have one?

292
00:19:21,160 --> 00:19:23,760
Not everyone can have babies.

293
00:19:23,760 --> 00:19:26,360
We adopted you
because we wanted you.

294
00:19:26,360 --> 00:19:29,480
And we both love you very much.

295
00:19:29,480 --> 00:19:31,560
I love you too.

296
00:19:35,200 --> 00:19:37,800
Dad, look! Radical!

297
00:19:39,360 --> 00:19:41,960
Yeah, radical.
You want to give it a try?

298
00:19:41,960 --> 00:19:43,000
Yeah.

299
00:19:45,600 --> 00:19:46,640
Now, do it.

300
00:19:51,320 --> 00:19:53,400
Yeah!

301
00:19:53,920 --> 00:19:57,560
Whoa! Chief, you're
a natural at this.

302
00:19:59,640 --> 00:20:01,200
( Bell Ringing )

303
00:20:01,720 --> 00:20:03,800
( Background Conversations )

304
00:20:07,440 --> 00:20:10,040
Good morning. Happy monday.

305
00:20:11,080 --> 00:20:13,680
- Hi.
- Hi. Hello.

306
00:20:15,240 --> 00:20:16,800
Go. Go.

307
00:20:19,920 --> 00:20:21,480
He'll be fine.

308
00:20:23,560 --> 00:20:25,640
You guys, settle down.

309
00:20:26,160 --> 00:20:26,680
Hi, Mikey.

310
00:20:26,680 --> 00:20:29,280
I'd like you to meet Mikey Trenton.

311
00:20:29,280 --> 00:20:32,920
Mikey just moved here.
But, with our help,

312
00:20:32,920 --> 00:20:35,520
I'm sure he'll have no problem
at all catching up; right?

313
00:20:35,520 --> 00:20:37,080
- Right!
- Right!

314
00:20:37,600 --> 00:20:39,680
Okay. Why don't you
give him a big welcome?

315
00:20:40,200 --> 00:20:42,280
- Hi, Mikey.
- Hi, Mikey.

316
00:20:43,320 --> 00:20:44,360
Go sit down.

317
00:20:47,480 --> 00:20:49,040
All right.

318
00:20:50,080 --> 00:20:53,200
Does anybody have their arts
and crafts project ready yet?

319
00:20:53,200 --> 00:20:53,720
I do.

320
00:20:54,240 --> 00:20:55,800
You do, huh? Let's see it.

321
00:20:59,440 --> 00:21:01,000
This is wonderful.

322
00:21:01,520 --> 00:21:02,560
So what time is it, class?

323
00:21:02,560 --> 00:21:04,640
( Chanting "Marble Time" )

324
00:21:09,840 --> 00:21:12,440
When we do something special,
Miss Gilder puts marbles in.

325
00:21:12,960 --> 00:21:16,080
When it's full, the door opens
and we all get prize.

326
00:21:16,080 --> 00:21:17,640
You get it, Mikey?

327
00:21:17,640 --> 00:21:19,200
Yes, Miss Gilder.

328
00:21:19,200 --> 00:21:20,760
I wonder what the prize is.

329
00:21:21,280 --> 00:21:22,840
Probably something dumb.

330
00:21:22,840 --> 00:21:23,880
I think she's neat.

331
00:21:24,400 --> 00:21:26,480
That's because she's
a friend of your mom's.

332
00:21:26,480 --> 00:21:28,040
I love my mom.

333
00:21:28,040 --> 00:21:29,600
Hey, I know a shortcut.

334
00:21:30,120 --> 00:21:31,680
Through the cemetery?

335
00:21:32,200 --> 00:21:33,240
Yeah. You scared?

336
00:21:33,240 --> 00:21:35,840
- No.
- You sure?

337
00:21:43,120 --> 00:21:44,680
Okay.

338
00:21:48,320 --> 00:21:51,960
It must be weird to have
just one parent to love you.

339
00:21:51,960 --> 00:21:55,600
- Both my parents love me.
- My mom loves me.

340
00:21:55,600 --> 00:21:58,720
- So why don't you have a dad?
- He died.

341
00:21:58,720 --> 00:22:01,840
- Did you see him die?
- No. He died in a hospital.

342
00:22:01,840 --> 00:22:02,880
Did you touch him?

343
00:22:02,880 --> 00:22:06,000
No! How'd your parents die?

344
00:22:06,520 --> 00:22:08,600
Why do you think
my parents are dead?

345
00:22:08,600 --> 00:22:11,200
You're adopted,
so I just sort of figured.

346
00:22:11,200 --> 00:22:13,800
They're not.

347
00:22:22,120 --> 00:22:23,680
Mikey!

348
00:22:25,760 --> 00:22:27,320
Mikey!

349
00:22:30,440 --> 00:22:32,520
Mikey, quit it!

350
00:22:37,720 --> 00:22:40,320
Mikey. Mikey, come on.

351
00:22:41,880 --> 00:22:43,440
Mikey, where are you?

352
00:22:47,600 --> 00:22:49,160
Mikey!

353
00:22:55,400 --> 00:22:56,960
Mikey?

354
00:23:01,640 --> 00:23:04,240
Mikey, what do you doing?

355
00:23:05,280 --> 00:23:06,840
Are you okay?

356
00:23:10,480 --> 00:23:13,600
Dead people aren't
the ones to be scared of.

357
00:23:13,600 --> 00:23:15,160
Living people are.

358
00:23:16,200 --> 00:23:18,520
NEIL: That's very good.

359
00:23:18,520 --> 00:23:20,880
It's self-contained.

360
00:23:20,880 --> 00:23:22,960
I love it.

361
00:23:23,480 --> 00:23:26,080
I read in this book
when a child draws water,

362
00:23:26,080 --> 00:23:30,240
it means he's adventurous
and broad-minded.

363
00:23:31,800 --> 00:23:33,880
Not bad. Maybe we have another

364
00:23:33,880 --> 00:23:35,960
Christopher Columbus
on our hands.

365
00:23:36,480 --> 00:23:38,040
What's a swimming girl mean?

366
00:23:38,040 --> 00:23:40,120
I was just looking that up.

367
00:23:41,680 --> 00:23:45,840
"A person swimming is symbolic
of a desire for freedom,"

368
00:23:45,840 --> 00:23:48,440
"a feeling of being caged."

369
00:23:48,440 --> 00:23:50,520
It means the parents need
to loosen their grip a bit.

370
00:23:50,520 --> 00:23:53,640
God. Are we being
overbearing already?

371
00:23:53,640 --> 00:23:55,200
Come on, honey.
Don't make fun of it.

372
00:23:55,200 --> 00:23:58,320
- Howdy!
- Hi, Mikey.

373
00:23:59,360 --> 00:24:01,960
I really, really like your drawing.

374
00:24:02,480 --> 00:24:04,560
Can I go ride my bike?

375
00:24:04,560 --> 00:24:06,120
Absolutely.

376
00:24:06,120 --> 00:24:07,680
Come home whenever
you want to;

377
00:24:08,200 --> 00:24:09,240
right, Neil?

378
00:24:10,280 --> 00:24:13,400
Sure. Whenever you want.

379
00:24:14,960 --> 00:24:16,000
( Croaking Sound )

380
00:24:16,000 --> 00:24:17,040
Shhhh.

381
00:24:20,160 --> 00:24:22,760
( Whispering )
Hear it? It's talking.

382
00:24:22,760 --> 00:24:25,360
Shut up! It's not funny anymore.

383
00:24:25,880 --> 00:24:27,440
( Croaking Sound )

384
00:24:27,440 --> 00:24:29,520
- Butch!
- ( Cat Screeching )

385
00:24:29,520 --> 00:24:31,600
No, Rosie! Butch, come here!

386
00:24:45,120 --> 00:24:46,160
( Buzzing Sound )

387
00:24:49,280 --> 00:24:50,320
There you go.

388
00:24:50,320 --> 00:24:53,960
This converts electricity
into visible light,

389
00:24:53,960 --> 00:24:55,520
kind of like a light bulb.

390
00:24:55,520 --> 00:24:58,120
The light bulb sends
a current through a wire.

391
00:24:58,120 --> 00:25:00,720
This sends electricity
between two wires.

392
00:25:01,240 --> 00:25:01,760
( Bell Ringing )

393
00:25:02,280 --> 00:25:04,880
- It's pretty cool, huh?
- STUDENTS: Yeah!

394
00:25:05,400 --> 00:25:10,080
Make sure you read
chapter 3 in your biology book.

395
00:25:10,600 --> 00:25:13,720
Don't forget your
movie reports are due friday.

396
00:25:13,720 --> 00:25:15,800
See you bright and early
tomorrow morning.

397
00:25:15,800 --> 00:25:16,840
'Bye.

398
00:25:19,960 --> 00:25:21,520
Mikey.

399
00:25:22,560 --> 00:25:23,840
Can you come here for a minute?

400
00:25:29,840 --> 00:25:31,400
Um...

401
00:25:32,960 --> 00:25:36,080
everybody wants to win,

402
00:25:36,080 --> 00:25:38,680
but it really isn't worth it
if you're just gonna cheat.

403
00:25:38,680 --> 00:25:41,280
The best way to
get people to like you

404
00:25:41,280 --> 00:25:43,360
is to just be yourself.

405
00:25:43,360 --> 00:25:44,920
Yes, Miss Gilder.

406
00:25:44,920 --> 00:25:48,040
Yeah? You think you can try that?

407
00:25:48,040 --> 00:25:49,080
Okay.

408
00:25:49,600 --> 00:25:54,280
I'm not gonna tell
your folks about this; okay?

409
00:25:54,280 --> 00:25:56,360
But you are.

410
00:25:57,920 --> 00:26:00,000
I'm gonna trust you on this.

411
00:26:02,080 --> 00:26:04,160
Okay.

412
00:26:04,680 --> 00:26:06,240
You can go.

413
00:26:08,320 --> 00:26:09,880
See you tomorrow.

414
00:26:10,400 --> 00:26:13,520
( Instrumental Music
Playing in Background )

415
00:26:13,520 --> 00:26:15,600
( Background Conversation )

416
00:26:15,600 --> 00:26:17,160
( Background Conversation )

417
00:26:21,840 --> 00:26:23,400
Whoo!

418
00:26:24,160 --> 00:26:26,000
( Background Conversation )

419
00:26:32,240 --> 00:26:34,320
( Ducks Quacking )

420
00:26:41,080 --> 00:26:43,680
Excuse me, Miss. You left this.

421
00:26:44,720 --> 00:26:46,800
For heaven's sake.
Thank you, young man.

422
00:26:46,800 --> 00:26:48,360
Well, Junior G-man,

423
00:26:48,880 --> 00:26:51,480
I think you've earned
yourself a half dollar.

424
00:26:51,480 --> 00:26:53,560
No, that's okay, sir.

425
00:26:54,080 --> 00:26:57,200
This is quite a little gentleman
you've raised here.

426
00:26:57,200 --> 00:26:59,000
Such an angel.

427
00:26:59,000 --> 00:27:01,880
You know, dear,
he's got your eyes.

428
00:27:02,400 --> 00:27:03,960
Thank you.

429
00:27:03,960 --> 00:27:05,520
We're very proud of him.

430
00:27:05,520 --> 00:27:09,160
You should be. Bye-bye. Thanks.

431
00:27:10,200 --> 00:27:12,280
I'm glad I have your eyes.

432
00:27:13,320 --> 00:27:14,360
Mikey.

433
00:27:15,400 --> 00:27:18,000
You handled that very well, chief.

434
00:27:18,520 --> 00:27:20,600
Let's go see the lakes.

435
00:27:24,240 --> 00:27:27,880
I have no idea there were
so many styles and colors.

436
00:27:27,880 --> 00:27:28,400
Oh, God.

437
00:27:28,400 --> 00:27:30,480
You should see the stuff
that walks into my class.

438
00:27:30,480 --> 00:27:32,560
RACHEL: I bet.

439
00:27:33,080 --> 00:27:35,680
I just want it to be right.
He's real special kid,

440
00:27:35,680 --> 00:27:38,280
and he needs some
special attention.

441
00:27:38,800 --> 00:27:40,880
Well, he seems really
interested in class.

442
00:27:40,880 --> 00:27:44,000
Has he told you
about the marble game?

443
00:27:44,520 --> 00:27:46,080
Marble game? Yeah.

444
00:27:46,080 --> 00:27:46,600
He has?

445
00:27:47,120 --> 00:27:49,720
Yeah. he says that he wants
to do his homework really well

446
00:27:49,720 --> 00:27:51,800
so that everybody gets a prize.

447
00:27:58,560 --> 00:28:02,200
Hey, are you still
thinking about getting a gun?

448
00:28:02,200 --> 00:28:03,760
Great.

449
00:28:08,440 --> 00:28:10,000
I can't have this in the house.

450
00:28:10,520 --> 00:28:14,160
Oh, Rachel.
I can't believe you doing this.

451
00:28:17,280 --> 00:28:19,880
You're out of your mind.
Now I'm packing.

452
00:28:19,880 --> 00:28:21,440
Let's go.

453
00:28:22,480 --> 00:28:23,520
MISS GILDER: I like the purple eyes.

454
00:28:23,520 --> 00:28:26,640
It's a nice touch.
And who's that, Sarah?

455
00:28:26,640 --> 00:28:29,760
That's my mommy
cooking thanksgiving dinner.

456
00:28:29,760 --> 00:28:31,840
- Does she?
- Yeah.

457
00:28:31,840 --> 00:28:34,440
- What's your?
- Stuffing.

458
00:28:36,000 --> 00:28:39,120
What have you got, Mikey?
I bet it's an indian.

459
00:28:42,240 --> 00:28:45,880
The pilgram's bad,
so the turkey's fixing him.

460
00:28:52,640 --> 00:28:54,720
Larry bird takes a pass
at the top of the key,

461
00:28:54,720 --> 00:28:55,760
hands it off to McHale--

462
00:28:55,760 --> 00:28:58,880
No, he keeps it,
and he drives to the basket!

463
00:28:59,400 --> 00:29:01,480
Yeah! The champs!

464
00:29:01,480 --> 00:29:04,600
- Oh, hi.
- I wanted you to see something.

465
00:29:06,680 --> 00:29:08,240
Uh-huh.

466
00:29:08,240 --> 00:29:09,800
Nice. It's a little weird, but--

467
00:29:10,320 --> 00:29:11,360
Who did it?

468
00:29:11,360 --> 00:29:13,440
- You?
- Mikey Trenton.

469
00:29:13,960 --> 00:29:16,040
So you told us to come to you

470
00:29:16,040 --> 00:29:18,120
with any sign of
a psychological problem.

471
00:29:18,640 --> 00:29:19,680
Yeah.

472
00:29:20,200 --> 00:29:22,280
According to the literature
I've been reading,

473
00:29:22,280 --> 00:29:25,400
Mikey could be suffering
from unattached syndrome.

474
00:29:25,920 --> 00:29:29,040
"Unattached syndrome."

475
00:29:29,560 --> 00:29:31,400
I never heard of it.

476
00:29:32,160 --> 00:29:33,720
It's psychotic behavior.

477
00:29:33,720 --> 00:29:38,400
I'm sorry. I hope I'm not
being rude, but...

478
00:29:38,920 --> 00:29:40,280
how long have you been a teacher?

479
00:29:40,280 --> 00:29:41,000
Two years.

480
00:29:41,520 --> 00:29:44,640
And you're sure of
what you're saying?

481
00:29:45,160 --> 00:29:47,760
No, I'm not sure.
But I certainly think

482
00:29:47,760 --> 00:29:49,840
it's something to be
wary of; don't you?

483
00:29:49,840 --> 00:29:53,480
So do I. But I don't think you
should be an alarmist about it.

484
00:29:54,320 --> 00:29:56,600
Look, I was a nine-year-old
kid once myself.

485
00:29:56,600 --> 00:30:00,240
I used to do drawings like this,
but I'm not psychotic.

486
00:30:00,760 --> 00:30:03,360
I like monster movies.
I especially like Godzilla,

487
00:30:03,360 --> 00:30:05,960
you know, the one with the
fire coming out of his mouth.

488
00:30:05,960 --> 00:30:08,560
So why encourage us to read this
if you don't take it seriously?

489
00:30:08,560 --> 00:30:11,160
I encourage you to read it, yes.

490
00:30:11,160 --> 00:30:14,960
I don't encourage you to
take every word literally.

491
00:30:14,960 --> 00:30:16,880
So you're not gonna
do anything about this?

492
00:30:17,400 --> 00:30:18,440
I'm not gonna
do anything right now.

493
00:30:18,960 --> 00:30:20,000
I think it's a little premature.

494
00:30:20,520 --> 00:30:23,120
I guess experience know;
huh, champ?

495
00:30:36,120 --> 00:30:38,720
Mikey Trenton gets the sign;

496
00:30:38,720 --> 00:30:41,840
checks the runner, winds up,

497
00:30:42,360 --> 00:30:43,920
throws a fastball.

498
00:30:43,920 --> 00:30:46,000
- ( Crowd Roars )
- Kelvin Swings.

499
00:30:46,000 --> 00:30:47,560
Strike!

500
00:30:51,200 --> 00:30:52,240
( Rachel Laughing )

501
00:30:52,240 --> 00:30:53,800
Hits the batter on the head.
Kelvin is down.

502
00:30:53,800 --> 00:30:56,400
Blood is everywhere.
The crowd roars. Yeah!

503
00:30:57,960 --> 00:30:59,000
Mikey, come inside and wash up.

504
00:31:03,680 --> 00:31:05,240
Okay, Mom.

505
00:31:07,320 --> 00:31:08,360
- Hi, Eva.
- Hi, Shawn.

506
00:31:09,400 --> 00:31:10,960
I hope you're not
looking for Mr. Jenkins.

507
00:31:11,480 --> 00:31:12,000
No.

508
00:31:12,520 --> 00:31:15,120
I need all the information you
can give me on Mikey Trenton.

509
00:31:15,120 --> 00:31:17,720
Sure. But it won't say much.

510
00:31:17,720 --> 00:31:19,800
We don't have any
of his past records.

511
00:31:19,800 --> 00:31:21,880
What do you mean?

512
00:31:21,880 --> 00:31:24,480
In a closed adoption,
all records are sealed.

513
00:31:25,000 --> 00:31:28,120
There you go.

514
00:31:29,160 --> 00:31:33,840
- Can't we.
- I doubt it.

515
00:31:34,360 --> 00:31:35,400
Besides, we don't even
know where he came from.

516
00:31:35,400 --> 00:31:36,960
( Whistle Blowing )

517
00:31:36,960 --> 00:31:39,560
Okay, guys. Come on in.

518
00:31:39,560 --> 00:31:42,160
Okay, ready to play?
Okay, let's line up.

519
00:31:42,160 --> 00:31:43,720
Mike, start over there.

520
00:31:43,720 --> 00:31:46,840
Guys, line up from Mike on.
Straight line now; remember?

521
00:31:46,840 --> 00:31:52,040
Come on. Straight line.
S-t-r-a-i-g-h-t line.

522
00:31:52,040 --> 00:31:54,120
Hey, hey. Look.
Pay attention here.

523
00:31:54,120 --> 00:31:56,720
See? Straight line.
That's it. Listen to me.

524
00:31:56,720 --> 00:31:57,760
Here, Steve.

525
00:31:59,320 --> 00:32:02,440
Shirt. Skin. Shirt. Skin.

526
00:32:02,440 --> 00:32:05,040
- Shirt. Skin.
- I'm a shirt.

527
00:32:05,560 --> 00:32:07,840
You're a skin, Trenton.

528
00:32:07,840 --> 00:32:09,200
I want to be a shirt.

529
00:32:09,200 --> 00:32:10,240
I said you're a skin.

530
00:32:10,240 --> 00:32:12,320
I'm not taking off my shirt.

531
00:32:12,320 --> 00:32:14,920
Look, take your shirt off.
Get some fun.

